[
    {
        "content": "<p>Does anyone know if people in algebraic geometry/commutative algebra/K-theory have studied modules equipped with a bilinear form?<br>\nUnder the <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Serre-Swan+theorem\">Serre-Swan theorem</a> these should correspond to vector bundles with an inner product, like for example the tangent bundle of a Riemannian manifold.</p>",
        "id": 525283017,
        "sender_full_name": "Paolo Perrone",
        "timestamp": 1750668587
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hermitian K-theory could be relevant <br>\n<a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Hermitian+K-theory\">https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Hermitian+K-theory</a></p>",
        "id": 525329564,
        "sender_full_name": "Ryo Suzuki",
        "timestamp": 1750684585
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>How about lattices with an inner product? Those seem to be pretty common.. I guess you might want <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unimodular_lattice\">integral lattices</a>.</p>",
        "id": 525398522,
        "sender_full_name": "Simon Burton",
        "timestamp": 1750708249
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There's a lot of work on modules with bilinear forms.  It's pretty easy to see that if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R = C(X)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is the ring of <em>real</em> continuous functions on a compact Hausdorff space <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>, a  module <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span> equipped with a nondegenerate bilinear form <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>M</mi><msub><mo>⊗</mo><mi>R</mi></msub><mi>M</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">g: M \\otimes_R M \\to R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\"><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span> is the same as a real vector bundle over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> equipped with an inner product.   The only clever part is that <strong>nondegenerate</strong> here should mean that the map </p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">♭</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>M</mi><mo>→</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>M</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> \\flat : M \\to [M,R] </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.75em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">♭</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>that arises from currying <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>g</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">g</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span></span></span></span> should be an isomorphism.  Here the brackets mean the internal hom in the category of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span>-modules, and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>M</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[M,R]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> is usually called the <strong>dual</strong> of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span>.  There's a theorem that any module over any commutative ring that's isomorphic to its dual must be finitely generated and projective!    Thus, we can apply Swan's theorem and conclude <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> is the module of sections of some vector bundle over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>.   The final step is to show that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>g</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">g</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span></span></span></span> comes from an inner product on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>If this was too terse, the following equation may help:</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">♭</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>s</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>g</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>s</mi><mo>⊗</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> \\flat (s) (t) = g(s \\otimes t) </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">♭</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>for any <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>s</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">s,t \\in M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8095em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 525404357,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1750711123
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I should just warn you that if we let <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span> be the ring of <em>complex</em> continuous functions on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>, the story changes, because an inner product on a complex vector bundle is not the same as a nondegenerate symmetric bilinear form on its module of sections: it corresponds to a nondegenerate <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sesquilinear_form\">sesquilinear</a> form.</p>",
        "id": 525404969,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1750711439
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thank you! Where can I find more on this?</p>",
        "id": 525413286,
        "sender_full_name": "Paolo Perrone",
        "timestamp": 1750716078
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't know.   I looked around a bit, but didn't see anything.  It's just \"obvious\".</p>",
        "id": 525413361,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1750716132
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'd be happy to explain this stuff further....</p>",
        "id": 525413372,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1750716144
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My question is, do people use this to do Riemannian geometry in an algebraic way?</p>",
        "id": 525454075,
        "sender_full_name": "Paolo Perrone",
        "timestamp": 1750749011
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There's a kind of offshoot of Connes' approach to noncommutative geometry, which is some people (physicists mainly) using Swan's theorem to \"algebraicize\" differential geometry in the way we've been discussing.   I can easily <em>imagine</em> them doing Riemannian geometry in the way I was just explaining.  But I don't actually remember seeing this stuff.    I worked on this back in the late 1980s but never published anything on it.</p>",
        "id": 525464694,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1750753135
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Algebraic geometers are more interested in Kahler geometry than Riemannian geometry: that's where you have a complex variety, with its complex tangent bundle, and you put a nondegenerate <em>sesquilinear</em> form on that complex tangent bundle, which called a hermitian form.     If it's very nice you call it a Kahler structure.</p>",
        "id": 525465051,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1750753253
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I poked around for 3 minutes looking for work on what you're wondering about, but I didn't see it.  It's so easy to do - with the proper training - that it's hard to believe it doesn't exist.</p>",
        "id": 525465206,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1750753308
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Did you follow up on links at the nLab page you first referenced, <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Serre-Swan+theorem\">Serre-Swan theorem</a>? Like <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/smooth+Serre-Swan+theorem\">smooth Serre-Swan theorem</a>:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/qhAxnECQ0C3y3UH8bmy6CUP5/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/qhAxnECQ0C3y3UH8bmy6CUP5/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"682x97\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/21317/qhAxnECQ0C3y3UH8bmy6CUP5/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><p>From there <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/derivations+of+smooth+functions+are+vector+fields\">derivations of smooth functions are vector fields</a>:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/Z2dh5S88ESmwvfgJsZhhSbg5/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/Z2dh5S88ESmwvfgJsZhhSbg5/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"680x85\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/21317/Z2dh5S88ESmwvfgJsZhhSbg5/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><p>And thence to the thickets of 'geometry of physics'.</p>",
        "id": 525468511,
        "sender_full_name": "David Corfield",
        "timestamp": 1750754432
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, that's what I'm interested in. How much of the 'metric' aspects have people made algebraic?</p>",
        "id": 525469122,
        "sender_full_name": "Paolo Perrone",
        "timestamp": 1750754654
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Perhaps some pointers from <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/embedding+of+smooth+manifolds+into+formal+duals+of+R-algebras\">embedding of smooth manifolds into formal duals of R-algebras</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/qkMfHwq3Bd7TAtLCojLrissn/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/qkMfHwq3Bd7TAtLCojLrissn/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"689x534\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/21317/qkMfHwq3Bd7TAtLCojLrissn/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><p>This is all Urs's stuff, so you might ask at a suitable thread on the nForum.</p>",
        "id": 525471580,
        "sender_full_name": "David Corfield",
        "timestamp": 1750755510
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Good idea, thanks!</p>",
        "id": 525471670,
        "sender_full_name": "Paolo Perrone",
        "timestamp": 1750755542
    }
]